<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-350-848  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 350 848.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  June 12 1989 v11 n24 p71(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Much ado about color. (desktop publishing programs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gruman, Galen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both Aldus Corp's Pagemaker 3.0 and Xerox Corp's Ventura Publisher2.0 offer spot color overlays.andP;  Spot color lets users add one ormore colors individually to a document, although the colors cannotbe mixed or combined.andP;  Printers add color to documents in twoways.andP;  With four-color printing, images are separatedphotographically into four negatives, one each for yellow,magenta, cyan and black.andP;  The dots are slightly rotated for eachcolor, preventing them from overprinting dot for dot.andP;  In spotcolor printing, the printer uses a pre-mixed ink for the colorusers want.andP;  Both Pagemaker and Ventura let users create any shadeof color desired by combining different percentages of colors, andgive users a choice of three models.andP;  They cannot, however, outputthe four separate positive or negatives a printer needs torecreate color.andP;  Rather, they output one sheet of whatever mediumthe printer can produce for each color.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Ventura Publisher 2.0 (Desktop publishing software) (productspecifications)PageMaker 3.0 (Desktop publishing software) (productspecifications).andO;Topic:     ColorDesktop PublishingGraphics SoftwarePrintouts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>